.TH DUMPEXE 1 "March 2026" "RetroCodeMess" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
dumpexe \- MS-DOS binary analyzer: MZ EXE, .COM, and device driver (.SYS)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dumpexe
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.br
.B dumpexe
.RB [ \-v | \-\-version ]
.br
.B dumpexe
.RB [ options ]
.I file
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dumpexe
is a comprehensive utility for analyzing MS-DOS 16-bit binary files.
It supports three file formats — MZ EXE executables, plain .COM programs,
and DOS device driver (.SYS) files — and provides TDUMP-style output with
multiple analysis modes:
.IP \(bu 2
Static header analysis with detailed field information
.IP \(bu 2
Relocation table display with padding analysis (MZ EXE)
.IP \(bu 2
Hex+ASCII dumps with zero-compression (like hexdump -C)
.IP \(bu 2
x86-16 disassembly using Capstone (static code analysis)
.IP \(bu 2
DOS load simulation with register tracking (dynamic execution trace)
.PP
The file format is detected automatically from the file content:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B MZ EXE
\(em first two bytes are
.B 4Dh 5Ah
('MZ')
.IP \(bu 2
.B .SYS device driver
\(em first four bytes are
.B FFFFFFFFh
.IP \(bu 2
.B .COM (plain binary)
\(em fallback for all other DOS binaries
.RE

.SH OPTIONS
.SS General Options
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display usage information and exit. Also shown when no arguments are provided.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.

.SS Display Sections
If no section options are given, the file header information is displayed, and for MZ EXE and .COM binaries a default 64-byte hex+ASCII preview of the entry point is also shown.
Multiple options can be combined.

.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-relocation
Show relocation table with all entries, including header padding before and after the table.
.B MZ EXE only.
The relocation table contains segment fixup locations that DOS applies when loading the program.
.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-hexdump
Show complete hex+ASCII dump from entry point to end of file.
Uses canonical hexdump -C format with zero-compression (repeated lines shown as *).
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-disassemble
Show x86-16 disassembly from entry point to end of file using Capstone.
This is
.B static analysis
\- shows all instructions without execution.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Show all sections in order: static info, relocation table (EXE), hexdump, and disassembly.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no-int-annotations
Suppress INT annotation comments in disassembly output.

.SS Simulation Options
.TP
.B \-\-simulate
Enable DOS load simulation mode. This performs
.B dynamic analysis
by simulating how DOS loads and starts the program. Shows:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Initial CPU register state (CS, IP, SS, SP, DS, ES, FLAGS, etc.)
.IP \(bu 2
Relocation fixups applied to the image (MZ EXE only)
.IP \(bu 2
Register tracing — simple instruction emulation showing register changes
.RE
.TP
.BI \-\-base= XXXX
Set the load base segment for simulation (hexadecimal value, default: 1000h).
This is the segment address where DOS loads the program.
Common values: 1000, 2000, etc.

.SS COM-Specific Options
These options only affect .COM file analysis; they are silently ignored for MZ EXE and .SYS files.
.TP
.B \-\-psp
Force the .COM file to be treated as containing an embedded PSP.
The entry point will be set to file offset 0100h.
Overrides the automatic PSP detection heuristic.
.TP
.B \-\-no-psp
Force the .COM file to be treated as
.B not
containing an embedded PSP.
The entry point will be set to file offset 0000h.
Overrides the automatic PSP detection heuristic.
These two flags are mutually exclusive.

.SH COM PSP DETECTION
A standard .COM file on disk starts directly with code/data — the PSP is built by DOS in
memory at program load time and is
.B not
part of the file.  Occasionally a .COM is saved as a raw memory snapshot that begins with a
256-byte PSP.
.B dumpexe
distinguishes these cases using two checks:
.IP 1. 4
First two bytes are
.B CDh 20h
(INT 20h instruction — the canonical PSP opener).
.IP 2. 4
The command-tail at file offset
.B 80h
is plausible: the length byte is ≤ 7Eh and the byte at
.B 81h + length
is
.B 0Dh
(carriage return).
.PP
Both checks must pass for a PSP to be declared present.  A file shorter than 256 bytes cannot
contain a PSP and is always treated as no-PSP.
Use
.B \-\-psp
or
.B \-\-no-psp
to override this heuristic.

.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
.SS Static Header Information
Always displayed first.
.B MZ EXE:
comprehensive header analysis including DOS File Size, Load Image Size,
Relocation Table entry count and address, Header Size, Memory Requirements,
Entry Point locations (file offset and image offset), and initial SS:SP / CS:IP values.
.br
.B COM:
File Size, Load Model (PSP embedded or not), Entry Point File Offset, and
initial CS:IP / SS:SP / DS / ES values.
.br
.B SYS:
Driver type (character or block), attributes, strategy and interrupt entry
point offsets, device name (char) or unit count and signature (block), and file size.

.SS Relocation Table (-r, MZ EXE only)
Formatted table showing each relocation entry with:
.IP \(bu 2
Entry number
.IP \(bu 2
Segment:Offset pair
.IP \(bu 2
File location in hex
.IP \(bu 2
Linear offset within image
.PP
Also shows any padding between header and relocation table, and between table and image.

.SS Hex+ASCII Dump (-x)
Complete dump from entry point to EOF in canonical hexdump -C format:
.IP \(bu 2
8-digit hex addresses (lowercase)
.IP \(bu 2
16 bytes per line with space after 8th byte
.IP \(bu 2
ASCII panel with | delimiters
.IP \(bu 2
Zero-compression: repeated identical lines shown as single * (saves enormous space)
.PP
Example:
.nf
00000420  1e b8 00 00 50 06 2e a1  00 00 8e c0 8e d8 58 a3  |....P.........X.|
00000430  00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00  00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00  |................|
*
00000450  ff ff ff ff 21 00 2a 00  33 00 44 00 55 00 66 00  |....!.*.3.D.U.f.|
.fi

.SS Disassembly (-d)
.B Static code analysis
using Capstone x86-16 disassembler. Shows file offset, raw bytes, mnemonic, and
operands for every instruction from the entry point to EOF.  INT instructions
are annotated with descriptions from the Ralf Brown Interrupt List (RBIL) database.

.SS Simulation (--simulate)
.B Dynamic execution trace
that simulates DOS loading and program startup:

.B Initial Register State:
.RS
For MZ EXE: CS and SS are shifted by the load base; DS and ES = load base.
.br
For .COM: CS = DS = ES = SS = load base; IP = 0100h; SP = FFFEh.
.RE

.B Relocation Fixups (MZ EXE only):
.RS
Shows each segment value being adjusted by the load base.
.RE

.B Register Tracing (with Capstone):
.RS
Best-effort emulation of first ~20 instructions showing register changes.
Not a full emulator — focuses on common register operations for quick insight.
.RE

.SH STATIC vs DYNAMIC ANALYSIS
.B Static Analysis (-d):
.RS
Disassembles all code without execution. Shows complete instruction stream. Good for
understanding program structure, finding all code paths, and analyzing algorithms.
.RE

.B Dynamic Analysis (--simulate):
.RS
Simulates execution from entry point. Shows register state changes. Good for
understanding program initialization and verifying relocation correctness.
.RE

.B Combined (-d --simulate):
.RS
Shows both full disassembly and dynamic trace — complete picture of the binary.
.RE

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error (invalid file, bad arguments, corrupted header)

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B dumpexe program.exe
Show only static header information (MZ EXE)
.TP
.B dumpexe -r program.exe
Show header and relocation table
.TP
.B dumpexe -x game.exe
Show header and complete hex dump
.TP
.B dumpexe -d game.exe
Show header and full disassembly (static analysis)
.TP
.B dumpexe --simulate game.exe
Show header and DOS load simulation (dynamic analysis)
.TP
.B dumpexe -a program.exe
Show everything: relocations, hexdump, disassembly
.TP
.B dumpexe -d --simulate --base=2000 game.exe
Disassemble and simulate loading at segment 2000h
.TP
.B dumpexe program.com
Analyze a .COM file (PSP presence auto-detected)
.TP
.B dumpexe --no-psp -d program.com
Analyze a .COM file, forcing no-PSP mode (entry at file offset 0)
.TP
.B dumpexe --psp -d memdump.com
Analyze a .COM memory dump that includes a PSP (entry at file offset 0100h)
.TP
.B dumpexe driver.sys
Analyze a DOS device driver
.TP
.B dumpexe -x program.com | less
Page through hexdump output of a .COM file

.SH FILES
.TP
.B dumpexe.h
Umbrella header that includes all modular sub-headers
.TP
.B com.h
MS-DOS .COM format constants (PSP size, entry offset, command-tail offsets)
.TP
.B com_analysis.h
.COM analysis functions: PSP heuristic detection and full analysis output
.TP
.B dumpexe.cpp
Main implementation file

.SH TECHNICAL DETAILS
.SS MZ EXE Format
.IP \(bu 2
Signature: 'MZ' (0x5A4D little-endian)
.IP \(bu 2
28-byte minimum header
.IP \(bu 2
Header sizes in paragraphs (16-byte units)
.IP \(bu 2
File size: ((num_blocks-1) × 512) + final_len
.IP \(bu 2
Entry point: header_size + (CS × 16) + IP

.SS COM Format
.IP \(bu 2
Flat binary image; DOS places the PSP at CS:0000 and loads the file at CS:0100
.IP \(bu 2
CS = DS = ES = SS = load segment at startup
.IP \(bu 2
SP initialised to 0xFFFE (top of 64 KB segment minus two bytes)
.IP \(bu 2
Execution always starts at CS:0100h

.SS SYS Device Driver Format
.IP \(bu 2
Starts with 0xFFFFFFFF (next-driver pointer = end of chain)
.IP \(bu 2
16-bit attribute word (bit 15 = character device)
.IP \(bu 2
Strategy and interrupt handler offsets
.IP \(bu 2
8-byte device name (character) or unit count + 7-byte signature (block)

.SS Register State Representation
Uses packed unions and bitfields for authentic x86 register access:
.IP \(bu 2
AX/BX/CX/DX with hi/lo byte access (AH/AL, etc.)
.IP \(bu 2
Segment registers: CS, DS, ES, SS
.IP \(bu 2
Pointers: IP, SP, BP, SI, DI
.IP \(bu 2
FLAGS with individual bit access (CF, ZF, SF, OF, etc.)

.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Read-only analysis — never modifies files
.IP \(bu 2
Works cross-platform (analyze DOS binaries on Linux/Unix)
.IP \(bu 2
Zero-compression in hex dumps saves space for AI context windows
.IP \(bu 2
Hex values displayed lowercase (canonical format)
.IP \(bu 2
Simulation is best-effort, not cycle-accurate emulation
.IP \(bu 2
Requires GCC 14+ and libcapstone-dev to build

